brodie wrote:As cool as this whole story is, I'd still be trying to press charges against the asshole driver.Good luck on that. You would need evidence he intended to keep the phone, merely being in his possession isn't theft, particularly because it was left in his cab. You'd need to have any records pulled that would indicate he tried to activate the phone for himself. And, unlike a high profile case like the Apple phone theft, the money to pay for all that would be coming out of your pocket, at least up until you collected enough to convince the DAs office to run with it.Seriously, once he gets the phone back the best thing he's going to get out of this is a good story. Nobody will take any action on the cabbie. (If you can't prove the cabbie intended to keep it and you were to call his cab company and make a big deal about it calling him a thief, etc. He'd potentially have grounds to sue you for slander.)
