topham wrote:Good luck on that. You would need evidence he intended to keep the phone, merely being in his possession isn't theftMost jurisdictions in the US consider it the duty of the finder to turn in misplaced/mislaid property to the owner of the establishment (in this case, the cab company). Lack of doing so, especially if you can prove he tried to activate in one of the stores he went to, would go a long way toward showing that he intended to keep property which he knew wasn't his.I'm not saying it's a strong case, but it's far from the nigh-impossibility you seem to indicate it is.
monkeytree
"Smells Like Bacon"
Ars Centurion
Tribus: The Land of Jeeps and Snowy
Registered: Apr 5, 2001Posts: 303
Posted: Sun Jul 31, 2011 12:06 pm
topham wrote:brodie wrote:As cool as this whole story is, I'd still be trying to press charges against the asshole driver.Good luck on that. You would need evidence he intended to keep the phone, merely being in his possession isn't theft, particularly because it was left in his cab. You'd need to have any records pulled that would indicate he tried to activate the phone for himself. And, unlike a high profile case like the Apple phone theft, the money to pay for all that would be coming out of your pocket, at least up until you collected enough to convince the DAs office to run with it.Seriously, once he gets the phone back the best thing he's going to get out of this is a good story. Nobody will take any action on the cabbie. (If you can't prove the cabbie intended to keep it and you were to call his cab company and make a big deal about it calling him a thief, etc. He'd potentially have grounds to sue you for slander.)I disagree. The cabbie was in possession of the phone for ~48 hours without making any attempt to return it to its rightful owner. He could have just as easily returned it to the dispatch manager or the airport's lost & found himself. It's pretty easy to infer his intent was to keep it and figure out a way to activate it for himself, especially since he stopped at several wireless stores. He also tried to hold it for ransom - i.e., 'pay me to give it back to you.' All the evidence he needs is right here with the GPS tracking and witness statements. It's up to the PD and the DA to determine whether it's worth their time and resources to pursue it.It'd be pretty hard to prove slander, since he'd have to prove that the person making the accusation knew that the accusation was false. Either way, California's courts are fruity enough that it's not worth risking it.I agree though that in all likelihood, it's best just to drop it and have a cool story to tell at parties.
